From 0000000000000000000000000000000000000011 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Petr Parkan Janda <petr.parkan.janda@oh-so.com>
Date: Mon, 23 Jun 2026 01:00:00 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] leds: steelhead-avr: drain key FIFO at probe (fix dead keys)

The Nexus Q capacitive mute/volume keys (the rotary volume ring) intermittently
did not work: pressing/rotating produced no input events and the AVR IRQ count
stayed 0, even though the AVR itself was detecting keys (its KEY_FIFO, read
directly over i2c, returned VOL_UP/VOL_DOWN/MUTE codes the whole time).

Root cause: the AVR holds its INT line low while KEY_FIFO is non-empty, and the
driver requests the irq as IRQF_TRIGGER_FALLING. If the FIFO already has entries
when the driver probes (stale presses queued before attach), INT is already low,
so no falling edge ever arrives -> avr_irq() never runs -> the FIFO is never
drained -> INT stays low forever. Whether this happens depends on the FIFO state
at probe, which is why the keys "worked sometimes" (a cold boot that probed with
an empty FIFO) and were dead other times.

Fix: after requesting the irq, drain the KEY_FIFO empty in probe. That releases
INT (goes high) and arms the falling edge for the first real key press.
(Confirmed on HW: draining the FIFO live made the IRQ start firing and all
mute/volume/rotation events appear immediately.)

Signed-off-by: Petr Parkan Janda <petr.parkan.janda@oh-so.com>
---
--- a/drivers/leds/leds-steelhead-avr.c
+++ b/drivers/leds/leds-steelhead-avr.c
@@ -452,6 +452,28 @@
 					"steelhead-avr", a);
 	if (ret)
 		return dev_err_probe(&client->dev, ret, "irq request failed\n");
+
+	/*
+	 * Drain any key events the AVR queued before we attached the IRQ. The
+	 * AVR holds its INT line low while KEY_FIFO is non-empty; with an
+	 * EDGE_FALLING irq a FIFO that is already non-empty at probe leaves INT
+	 * low with no further falling edge, so the irq never fires and the keys
+	 * stay dead until a cold boot that happens to probe with an empty FIFO
+	 * (the intermittent 'keys/volume sometimes work' symptom). Read the
+	 * FIFO empty here to release INT and arm the edge for the first press.
+	 */
+	while (true) {
+		u16 code;
+		bool down;
+		u8 b;
+
+		mutex_lock(&a->io_lock);
+		ret = avr_read_reg(a, AVR_REG_KEY_FIFO, &b);
+		mutex_unlock(&a->io_lock);
+		if (ret || avr_decode_key(b, &code, &down) == -EAGAIN)
+			break;
+	}
+
 	return 0;
 }
 
